ool texts, and Arabic-language grammars in general will include diacritics to some degree.  These are known as "vocalized" texts.Short vowels may be written with diacritics placed above or below the consonant that precedes them in the syllable, called ''''. All Arabic vowels, long and short, follow a consonant; in Arabic, words like "Ali" or "alif", for example, start with a consonant: '''';;, ''alif''.{|class="wikitable"|-!Short vowels(fully vocalized text)!Name!Name in Arabic script!Trans.!Value|- style="text-align:center;"|style="line-height:180%;padding:10px;"|064E;||فتحة|''a''||- style="text-align:center;"|style="line-height:180%;padding:10px;"|064F;||ضمة|''u''||- style="text-align:center;"|style="line-height:180%;padding:10px;"|0650;|kasrah|كسرة|''i''||}Long vowelsIn the fully vocalized Arabic text found in texts such as Koran, a long '''' following a consonant other than a ''hamza|hamzah'' is written with a short ''a'' sign ('''') on the consonant plus an ''alif'' after it; long '''' is written as a sign for short ''i'' (''kasrah'') plus a ; and long '''' as a sign for short ''u'' ('''') plus a ''''. Briefly, '''' = '''', '''' = '''' and '''' = ''''. Long '''' following a ''hamzah'' may be represented by an ''alif maddah'' or by a free ''hamzah'' followed by an ''alif''.The table below shows vowels placed above or below a dotted circle replacing a primary consonant letter or a ''Shadda|shaddah'' sign. For clarity in the table, the primary letters on the left used to mark these long vowels are shown only in their isolated form. Please note that most consonants do connect to the left with ''alif'', '''' and '''' written then with their medial or final form. Additionally, the letter '''' in the last row may connect to the letter on its left, and then will use a medial or initial form. Use the table of primary letters to look at their actual glyph and joining types.{|class="wikitable"|-!Long vowels(fully vocalized text)!Name!Trans.!Value|- style="text-align:cente